AST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: occupational name from Old French  <i>chaucier</i> ‘maker of  <i>chausses</i>’, an agent derivative of Old French  <i>chauces</i> ‘breeches, pantaloons, hose’. In 1484 these were ‘chauces of yron or legge harneys’ (   OED  ). Middle English  <i>chauce</i> was a general term for anything worn on the feet: boots, shoes, hose, or leggings. As Baldwin le Chaucer (1307   London Letter Books   B) was of  <i>Cordwanerstrete</i>, the early  <i>chaucer</i> was probably a worker in leather, a maker of leather breeches, boots, etc."],"variants":[{"name":"London Letter Books","meanings":["1  English: nickname, variant of the Norman name   Petchey   (Old French  <i>peché</i>, Middle English  <i>peche</i> ‘sin’). Medieval spellings with final  <i>-e</i> can represent either  <i>peché</i> or  <i>peche</i>, so some of the earliest of the following bearers may belong with  <i>Petchey</i> rather than  <i>Petch</i>, but the two forms of the name were in any case interchangeable. Compare John Peche, tailor, 1320, identical with J. Pecchee, 1328 in   London Letter Books   E; John Peche, 1558, Moses Pechey, 1584 in   IGI   (West Hanningfield, Essex).","2  English: variant of   Spetch   with loss of initial  <i>S-</i> (unless  <i>Spetch</i> itself is a variant of  <i>Petch</i> with a prosthetic  <i>S-</i>). The two names were certainly interchangeable.   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes Michael Petch or Spetch (1609–13) and Lancelot or Lance Petch or Spetch (1625–7) in the Leeds parish registers; and Benjamin Petch otherwise Spetch, 1764 in   WR Yorks Quarter Sessions   (Azerley, WR Yorks). Compare also Thome Peche, 1586, Margret Spetche, 1594 in   IGI   (Londonthorpe, Lincs); Thomas Spech, 1589, Richd. Petch, 1726 in   IGI   (Whitgift, WR Yorks)."]},{"name":"Causer","meanings":["English (West Midlands): probably a variant of <b>Chauser</b>, an occupational name for a maker of leggings or other apparel for the legs or feet, from an agent derivative probably of a northern variant of Old French <i>cauc(i)er</i>, <i>chaucier</i> ‘maker of hose, shoemaker’, although <i>Cauc(i)er</i>, the Norman and Picard form of the name, has not yet been noted in English medieval records. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of <b>Cosier</b>, an occupational name from Middle English <i>cosere</i> ‘horse dealer’."]},{"name":"OED","meanings":["1  English: possibly a suffixed form of Middle English  <i>sere</i> ‘dry, withered’, seen also for example in Godefridus Seredust, 1199 in   Curia Regis Rolls  . Such extended adjectives are sometimes found in Early Modern English, as in  <i>stouty</i> and the surviving  <i>lanky</i>. ‘… certain monosyllabic adjs. were extended by means of this suffix, app[arently] with the design of giving them a more adjectival appearance … The majority of such words arose in the 16th and 17th cent.” (   OED  ).","2  Irish: from  <b>Ó Saoraidhe</b>,  see  Seery  ."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":8,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901